{"title_page": "2012 in Canada", "text_new": "{{Year in Canada|2012}}\n{{History of Canada}}\nEvents from the year '''2012 in [[Canada]]'''.\n\n== Incumbents ==\n\n=== Crown ===\n* [[List of Canadian monarchs|Monarch]] \u2013 [[Elizabeth II]]\n\n=== Federal government ===\n* [[Governor General of Canada|Governor general]] \u2013 [[David Johnston]] \n* [[Prime Minister of Canada|Prime minister]] \u2013 [[Stephen Harper]]\n* [[Chief Justice of Canada|Chief Justice]] \u2013 [[Beverley McLachlin]] ([[British Columbia]])\n* [[Parliament of Canada|Parliament]] \u2013 [[41st Canadian Parliament|41st]]\n\n=== Provincial governments ===\n\n==== Lieutenant governors ====\n*[[Lieutenant Governor of Alberta]] \u2013 [[Donald Ethell]]\n*[[Lieutenant Governor of British Columbia]] \u2013 [[Steven Point]] (until November 2) then [[Judith Guichon]]\n*[[Lieutenant Governor of Manitoba]] \u2013 [[Philip S. Lee]]\n*[[Lieutenant Governor of New Brunswick]] \u2013 [[Graydon Nicholas]]\n*[[Lieutenant Governor of Newfoundland and Labrador]] \u2013 [[John Crosbie]]\n*[[Lieutenant Governor of Nova Scotia]] \u2013 [[Mayann Francis]] (until April 12) then [[John James Grant]]\n*[[Lieutenant Governor of Ontario]] \u2013 [[David Onley]]\n*[[Lieutenant Governor of Prince Edward Island]] \u2013 [[Frank Lewis (broadcaster)|Frank Lewis]]\n*[[Lieutenant Governor of Quebec]] \u2013 [[Pierre Duchesne]]\n*[[Lieutenant Governor of Saskatchewan]] \u2013 [[Gordon Barnhart]] (until March 22) then [[Vaughn Solomon Schofield]]\n\n==== Premiers ====\n*[[Premier of Alberta]] \u2013 [[Alison Redford]]\n*[[Premier of British Columbia]] \u2013 [[Christy Clark]]\n*[[Premier of Manitoba]] \u2013 [[Greg Selinger]]\n*[[Premier of New Brunswick]] \u2013 [[David Alward]]\n*[[Premier of Newfoundland and Labrador]] \u2013 [[Kathy Dunderdale]]\n*[[Premier of Nova Scotia]] \u2013 [[Darrell Dexter]]\n*[[Premier of Ontario]] \u2013 [[Dalton McGuinty]]\n*[[Premier of Prince Edward Island]] \u2013 [[Robert Ghiz]]\n*[[Premier of Quebec]] \u2013 [[Jean Charest]] (until September 19) then [[Pauline Marois]]\n*[[Premier of Saskatchewan]] \u2013 [[Brad Wall]]\n\n=== Territorial governments ===\n\n==== Commissioners ====\n* [[Commissioner of Yukon]] \u2013 [[Doug Phillips (politician)|Doug Phillips]]\n* [[Commissioner of Northwest Territories]] \u2013 [[George Tuccaro]]\n* [[Commissioner of Nunavut]] \u2013 [[Edna Elias]]\n\n==== Premiers ====\n*[[Premier of the Northwest Territories]] \u2013 [[Bob McLeod (politician)|Bob McLeod]]\n*[[Premier of Nunavut]] \u2013 [[Eva Aariak]]\n*[[Premier of Yukon]] \u2013 [[Darrell Pasloski]]\n\n== Events ==\n\n=== January to March ===\n* January 1 \u2013 The [[Quebec]] Sales Tax (QST) rises one percentage point to 9.5%.\n* January 10 - MP for [[Saint-Maurice\u2014Champlain]], the NDP's [[Lise St-Denis]], [[Crossing the floor|crosses the floor]] to join the Liberal caucus.<ref>{{cite news|last=Payton|first=Laura|title=NDP MP Lise St-Denis jumps to Liberals|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/story/2012/01/10/pol-lib-rae-coderre.html|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=January 10, 2012|date=January 10, 2012}}</ref>\n* January 29 \u2013 A guilty verdict in the trial of the [[Shafia family murders]] is returned.\n* February 4\n** The [[List of diplomatic missions in Ottawa|Syrian Embassy in Ottawa]] is [[vandalized]] as it was [[spray paint|sprayed]] with [[red]] paint.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/ottawa/story/2012/02/04/ottawa-syria-embassy-vandalism.html|title=Syrian embassy in Ottawa vandalized|publisher=[[CBC.ca]]|date=2012-02-04|accessdate=2012-02-05}}</ref>\n** An [[imam]] issues a [[fatwa]] condemning [[honour killings]] and [[domestic violence]], in reaction to the [[Shafia family murder]] guilty verdict.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/story/2012/02/04/toronto-fatwa-honour-killing-violence.html|title=Canadian fatwa condemns 'honour killings'|publisher=[[CBC.ca]]|date=2012-02-04|accessdate=2012-02-05}}</ref>\n* February 7\n** Eleven people, including 10 [[migrant worker]]s from [[Peru]], die when a passenger van crashes into a flatbed truck near [[Stratford, Ontario|Stratford]].<ref>{{cite news|author=|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/story/2012/02/07/ontario-hampstead-van-truck-crash.html |title='Miracle' anyone survived Ontario van-truck crash |publisher=Cbc.ca |date=2012-02-07 |accessdate=2012-08-10}}</ref>\n** Prime Minister Stephen Harper begins a four-day visit to [[China]].<ref>{{cite news|author=The Canadian Press |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/story/2012/02/07/harper-china-arrival.html |title=Harper lands in China looking for business |publisher=Cbc.ca |date=2012-02-07 |accessdate=2012-08-10}}</ref>\n* February 10 \u2013 A [[Red Arrow Motorcoach|Red Arrow]] bus skidded out of control and flipped on its side near Redwater, [[Alberta]].  At least 28 people were injured in the incident.\n* February 26 \u2013 Three [[Via Rail]] employees die when a [[Burlington derailment|train derails]] near [[Burlington, Ontario|Burlington]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/story/2012/02/26/viarail-toronto.html |title=3 Via employees die in Ontario derailment |publisher=Cbc.ca |date=2012-02-27 |accessdate=2012-08-10}}</ref>\n* March 3 \u2013 Near [[Montreal]], a charter bus crashes killing two people and injuring 48 others.<ref>{{cite news|author=|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/story/2012/03/03/montreal-bus-crash-plessisville.html |title=Quebec charter bus crash kills 2 |publisher=Cbc.ca |date=2012-03-03 |accessdate=2012-08-10}}</ref>\n* March 5 \u2013 The federal government announces they are closing the Canadian embassy in [[Damascus]], [[Syria]] amid the [[2011\u20132012 Syrian uprising|continuing violence]] in that country.<ref>[https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/politics/ottawa-notebook/canada-further-expands-sanctions-on-syria/article2359048/ Canada shuts down embassy, further expands sanctions on Syria]{{dead link|date=August 2012}}</ref>\n* March 19 \u2013 NDP candidate [[Craig Scott (politician)|Craig Scott]]<ref>{{cite news|title=NDP wins in Jack Layton's former riding|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/story/2012/03/19/toronto-layton-byelection.html|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=March 19, 2012|date=March 19, 2012}}</ref> wins a federal by-election in [[Toronto\u2014Danforth]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Fitzpatrick|first=Meagan|title=Byelection for Jack Layton's riding moved back a week|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/story/2012/02/06/pol-toronto-danforth-byelection.html|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=February 6, 2012|date=February 6, 2012}}</ref>\n* March 22 \u2013 [[Vaughn Solomon Schofield]] becomes [[lieutenant governor of Saskatchewan]], replacing [[Gordon Barnhart]].\n* March 23 - In [[Perth-Andover]], a high spring freshet coupled with an ice jam caused a rise in water levels surpassing those in the 1987 flood. A mandatory evacuation order was issued.<ref>{{cite news|last=Hudras |first=Adam |title=New Brunswick village Perth-Andover flooded |url=https://vancouversun.com/news/Brunswick+village+Perth+Andover+flooded/6354434/story.html |accessdate=24 March 2012 |newspaper=Vancouver Sun |date=24 March 2012 |location=Perth-Andover, NB |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120326180122/http://www.vancouversun.com/news/Brunswick%2Bvillage%2BPerth%2BAndover%2Bflooded/6354434/story.html |archivedate=26 March 2012 |df= }}</ref> About 500 people were affected.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dozens ordered out of N.B. flood area|url=http://thechronicleherald.ca/canada/76923-dozens-ordered-out-nb-flood-area|accessdate=24 March 2012|newspaper=The Chronicle Herald|date=24 March 2012|location=Perth-Andover, NB}}</ref>\n* March 24 \u2013 [[Thomas Mulcair]] is [[2012 New Democratic Party leadership election|elected]] leader of the [[New Democratic Party (Canada)|NDP]].<ref>{{cite news|author=|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/story/2012/03/24/pol-ndp-leadership-convention-vote-result.html |title=Mulcair bests Topp to win NDP leadership |publisher=Cbc.ca |date=2012-03-24 |accessdate=2012-08-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.nationalpost.com/2012/03/24/thomas-mulcair-elected-new-leader-of-ndp/ |title=Thomas Mulcair elected new leader of NDP |publisher=News.nationalpost.com |date= |accessdate=2012-08-10}}</ref>\n* March 29\n** Finance Minister [[Jim Flaherty]] announces the 2012 budget which includes cuts to the [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|CBC]], the reduction of over 19,000 federal jobs, and the discontinuation of the [[Penny (Canadian coin)|Penny]] by the [[Royal Canadian Mint]].<ref>{{cite news|author=|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/story/2012/03/29/federalbudget-flaherty-hilights.html |title=Federal budget highlights |publisher=Cbc.ca |date=2012-03-29 |accessdate=2012-08-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/story/2012/03/29/federalbudget-flaherty-cbc-cuts.html |title=CBC budget cut by $115M over 3 years |publisher=CBC.ca |date=2012-03-29 |accessdate=2012-08-10}}</ref>\n** The federal government announces they will gradually raise the age of eligibility for [[Old Age Security]] from 65 to 67 starting in 2023.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.ctv.ca/topstories/20120329/federal-budget-old-age-security-120329.html |title=Budget confirms Old Age Security push to age 67 |publisher=M.ctv.ca |date= |accessdate=2012-08-10}}</ref>\n\n=== April to June ===\n* April 1 \u2013 [[Juno Awards of 2012|Juno Awards]] in Ottawa, Ontario\n* April 12 \u2013 [[John James Grant]] becomes [[Lieutenant Governor of Nova Scotia]], replacing [[Mayann Francis]].\n* April 15 \u2013 100th anniversary of the [[Sinking of the RMS Titanic|sinking of the]] [[RMS Titanic|RMS ''Titanic'']]\n* April 19\n** The federal government announced they will close [[Kingston Penitentiary]], which has housed convicted killers such as [[Paul Bernardo]] and [[Russell Williams (colonel)|Russell Williams]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/story/2012/04/19/pol-prison-closing-toews.html |title=Historic Kingston Penitentiary to close |publisher=Cbc.ca |date=2012-04-20 |accessdate=2012-08-10}}</ref>\n** One hundred and fifty students are arrested in [[Gatineau]] after violent protests against Quebec's proposed tuition hikes.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/150-arrested-during-escalating-quebec-student-protest/article2408306/ |title=150 arrested during escalating Quebec student protest |publisher=Theglobeandmail.com |date= |accessdate=2012-08-10 |location=Toronto}}</ref>\n* April 23 \n** The [[Progressive Conservative Association of Alberta]] wins a [[majority government]] of 61 seats in the [[2012 Alberta general election|2012 Alberta election]]. The [[Wildrose Party]] wins 17 seats to become the [[Leader of the Opposition (Alberta)|Official Opposition]], both for the first time, [[Liberal Party of Alberta|Liberal Party]] five, and [[New Democratic Party of Alberta|New Democratic Party]] four.\n** [[Thunder Bay\u2014Superior North]] MP [[Bruce Hyer]] leaves the NDP caucus after being disciplined for voting against the NDP's position on the [[Canadian Firearms Registry|gun registry]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Bruce Hyer ditches NDP to sit as an Independent MP|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/story/2012/04/23/pol-ndp-bruce-hyer.html|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=April 23, 2012|date=April 23, 2012}}</ref>\n* April 24 \u2013 A sawmill in [[Prince George, British Columbia|Prince George]], [[British Columbia]] explodes killing two workers.<ref>{{cite news|author=|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/story/2012/04/25/bc-sawmill-fire-second-death.html |title=Prince George sawmill fire death toll rises to 2 |publisher=Cbc.ca |date=2012-04-25 |accessdate=2012-08-10}}</ref>\n* April 28 \u2013 Seven killed in [[Alberta]] [[Alberta Highway 63|Highway 63]] crash near [[Fort McMurray]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://calgaryherald.com/killed+Alberta+Highway+crash+near+Fort+McMurray/6535499/story.html |title=Newfoundland-born pastor Shannon Wheaton dies in Alberta crash that kills seven |publisher=Calgaryherald.com |date=2012-04-29 |accessdate=2012-08-10}}</ref>\n* May 12 \u2013 Two private planes collide in midair near [[St. Brieux, Saskatchewan]], killing five people.<ref>{{cite news|author=|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/saskatchewan/story/2012/05/12/sk-planes-120512.html |title=Midair collision kills 5 in Saskatchewan |publisher=Cbc.ca |date=2012-05-12 |accessdate=2012-08-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://edmonton.ctv.ca/servlet/an/local/CTVNews/20120513/saskatchewan-plane-crash-investigation-120513/20120513/?hub=EdmontonHome |title=As Sask. plane collision is probed, victims are identified |publisher=Edmonton.ctv.ca |date=2012-05-13 |accessdate=2012-08-10}}</ref>\n* May 18\n** An Ontario Superior Court judge declares the [[2011 Canadian federal election|2011 federal election]] results in the riding of [[Etobicoke Centre (electoral district)|Etobicoke Centre]] to be \"null and void\", potentially triggering a by-election.<ref>{{cite web|title=Etobicoke-Centre election result ruled 'null and void'|url=http://www.ctv.ca/CTVNews/TopStories/20120518/elections-canada-rules-etobicoke-centre-election-result-void-120518/|publisher=CTV News|accessdate=May 19, 2012|date=May 18, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Payton18May12\">{{cite news|url = http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/story/2012/05/18/pol-court-throws-out-etobicoke-centre-election-wrzesnewskyj.html|title = Tory MP asks Supreme Court to uphold Toronto riding result|accessdate = July 12, 2012|date = May 28, 2012| work = [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]]}}</ref>\n** The Quebec government passes [[Bill 78]] which places restrictions on the ongoing [[2012 Quebec student protests|protests]] over the forthcoming tuition hikes in the province.\n* May 20 - [[Charles, Prince of Wales]], and [[Camilla, Duchess of Cornwall]] arrive in [[Fredericton]] beginning a four-day [[List of royal tours of Canada (21st century)|royal tour]] across the country.<ref>{{cite news|title=Prince Charles and Camilla arrive in Canada|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/story/2012/05/20/nb-royals-arriving-sunday-331.html|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=May 21, 2012|date=May 20, 2012}}</ref>\n* May 24 - Nearly 700 people are held in two Quebec cities in the biggest single night of mass arrests since student protests over fees began in February.\n* May 28 - [[Jason Godin]], at 19 years old, becomes the youngest mayor in the history of [[New Brunswick]] and Canada.<ref>[http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/story/2012/05/15/nb-5-new-faces-election-1030.html \"5 newly elected municipal leaders to watch\"]. [[CBC News]], May 15, 2012.</ref>\n* May 30 - [[Lee Richardson (politician)|Lee Richardson]] resigns as MP for [[Calgary Centre]], to accept a job as [[Principal Secretary (Canada)|principal secretary]] to Alberta Premier [[Alison Redford]].<ref name=\"Richardson\">{{cite news|url = http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/story/2012/05/30/pol-lee-richardson-retires.html|title = Calgary MP Lee Richardson announces retirement|accessdate = May 30, 2012|last = Fitzpatrick|first = Meagan|date = May 30, 2012| work = [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]]}}</ref>\n* June 2 - A shooting at the [[Toronto Eaton Centre#June 2012 gang-related shooting|Toronto Eaton Centre]] leaves one dead and seven others injured.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/story/2012/06/02/toronto-eaton-center-shooting.html |title=Toronto Eaton Centre shooting kills 1, injures 7 |publisher=Cbc.ca |date=2012-06-03 |accessdate=2012-08-10}}</ref>\n* June 15 - A shooting at the [[University of Alberta]] in [[Edmonton]] leaves three dead.<ref>{{cite news|author=|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/edmonton/story/2012/06/15/edmonton-university-school-shooting.html |title=Security guard now suspect in University of Alberta shootings |publisher=Cbc.ca |date=2012-06-15 |accessdate=2012-08-10}}</ref>\n* June 16 - A stage collapses before a [[Radiohead]] concert in [[Toronto]] killing one person and injuring three more.<ref>{{cite news|author=|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/story/2012/06/16/toronto-stage-collapse-radiohead.html |title=1 dead as Radiohead stage collapses ahead of Toronto concert |publisher=Cbc.ca |date=2012-06-16 |accessdate=2012-08-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2012/06/16/world/americas/canada-stage-collapse/index.html?hpt=hp_t1 |title=1 killed when Toronto stage collapses before sold-out Radiohead concert |publisher=Cnn.com |date= June 17, 2012|accessdate=2012-08-10}}</ref>\n* June 18 \u2013 200th anniversary of the start of [[War of 1812]].\n* June 23 - A partial roof collapse at the [[Algo Centre Mall]] in [[Elliot Lake]], Ontario injures dozens and kills two.<ref>{{cite news|title=One believed dead, one trapped in Elliot Lake mall roof cave-in|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/story/2012/06/24/elliot-lake-mall-roof-collapse.html|date=June 24, 2012|accessdate=June 24, 2012|publisher=[[CBC.ca]]}}</ref>\n* June 25 - Floods across the [[British Columbia]] interior region cause hundreds of people to evacuate their homes and kills one man.<ref>{{cite news|author=The Canadian Press |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/story/2012/06/26/bc-flooding-evacuations-highways.html |title=Deadly B.C. flooding continues to prompt evacuations, highway closures |publisher=Cbc.ca |date=2012-06-26 |accessdate=2012-08-10}}</ref>\n\n=== July to September ===\n* July 1 \u2013 Celebrations of the 145th anniversary of [[Canadian Confederation|Confederation]].\n* July 12 \u2013 [[Johnsons Landing, British Columbia|Johnsons Landing]] in [[British Columbia]] is hit by a landslide. Four people are still unaccounted for<ref>{{cite news|author=The Canadian Press |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/story/2012/07/12/bc-landslide-johnsons-landing.html |title=B.C. landslide leaves 4 unaccounted for |publisher=Cbc.ca |date=2012-07-12 |accessdate=2012-08-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2012/07/13/world/americas/canada-landslide/index.html |title=4 people missing after Canadian landslide |publisher=Edition.cnn.com |date= July 14, 2012|accessdate=2012-08-10}}</ref>\n* July 16 \u2013\n** The [[Danzig Street shooting]] at a suburban block party leaves 2 dead and 24 injured in Toronto's worst mass shooting.<ref name=\"CommissoMurder\">\n{{cite news \n|last= Commisso\n|first= Christina\n|date= 8 November 2012\n|title= Murder charges laid in Toronto BBQ mass shooting\n|url= http://toronto.ctvnews.ca/murder-charges-laid-in-toronto-bbq-mass-shooting-1.1029580\n|work= CTV News\n|location= Toronto\n|access-date= 4 June 2017\n}}</ref>\n** [[Barrie, Ontario|Barrie]] bombs.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/article/1227402--barrie-bombs-residents-frustrated-by-lengthy-evacuation |title=Barrie bombs: Residents frustrated by lengthy evacuation |publisher=thestar.com |date= July 16, 2012|accessdate=2012-08-10 |location=Toronto}}</ref>\n* July 31 \u2013 [[Bev Oda]] resigns as [[Minister for International Cooperation (Canada)|Minister for International Co-operation]] and as MP for [[Durham (electoral district)|Durham]].<ref>{{cite news|first=Joanna |last=Smith |url=https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/politics/article/1220735--international-development-minister-bev-oda-resigns-as-conservative-mp-for-durham |title=Bev Oda resigns as Conservative MP for Durham |publisher=thestar.com |date= July 3, 2012|accessdate=July 3, 2012 |location=Toronto}}</ref>\n* August 31 \u2013 Citing health, [[Denise Savoie]] resigns as MP for [[Victoria (electoral district)|Victoria]].<ref>{{cite news|title=NDP MP Denise Savoie cites health in resigning Commonsseat|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/story/2012/08/23/pol-savoie-resigns-victoria.html|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=August 23, 2012|date=August 23, 2012}}</ref> and contracts for cupe etfo and osstf expires \n * September 4 \u2013\n**The [[Parti Qu\u00e9b\u00e9cois]] win a [[minority government]] in the [[2012 Quebec general election]],<ref>[http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/quebecvotes2012/story/2012/09/03/quebec-election-night-results-2012.html Pauline Marois to become Quebec's st female premier]. [[CBC News]], September 3, 2012.</ref> with the [[Quebec Liberal Party]] coming in a close second.\n** A [[2012 Montreal shooting|shooting]] takes place during Premier-Designate [[Pauline Marois]]' victory speech at the [[Parti Qu\u00e9b\u00e9cois]] rally, killing one man and injuring another.<ref>[http://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/quebec-shooting-suspect-heard-shouting-english-are-waking-up-1.943030 Quebec shooting suspect heard shouting 'English are waking up']. [[CTV News]], September 5, 2012.</ref><ref>[http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/story/2012/09/05/mtl-pq-victory-rally-attack.html Suspect in fatal PQ victory rally shooting not from Montreal]. [[CBC News]], September 5, 2012.</ref>\n* September 6 \u2013 60th anniversary of [[CBC Television]].\n* September 7 \u2013 The government closes the [[Canada\u2013Iran relations#2012 embassy closure|Canadian embassy]] in [[Iran]] and gave Iranian diplomats five days to leave Canada citing Iran as a \"threat to global peace\".<ref>[https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/politics/citing-threat-to-global-peace-canada-cuts-diplomatic-ties-with-iran/article4526167/ Citing 'threat to global peace,' Canada cuts diplomatic ties with Iran]. ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'', September 7, 2012.</ref><ref>[http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/story/2012/09/07/pol-baird-canada-iran-embassy.html Canada closes embassy in Iran, expels Iranian diplomats]. [[CBC News]], September 7, 2012.</ref>\n* September 19 \u2013 [[Pauline Marois]] is sworn in as [[premier of Quebec]], following a [[2012 Quebec general election|general election]], becoming Quebec's first [[List of female premiers in Canada|female premier]], and the first time in Canadian history that five provinces or territories have simultaneously had female premiers (until [[2013 in Canada#January to March|February 2013]]).\n* September 21 \u2013 A [[state funeral]] is held for former [[premier of Alberta]] [[Peter Lougheed]], at the [[Southern Alberta Jubilee Auditorium]] in Calgary.\n* September 24 \u2013 An outbreak of ''[[E. coli]]'' causes at least four illnesses in [[Alberta]], a massive beef recall, and the temporary shutdown of [[XL Foods]] in [[Brooks, Alberta]].\n* September 26 \u2013 A controversial [[Motion (parliamentary procedure)|motion]] (M-312) to re-open the [[abortion in Canada|abortion debate]] is defeated, in the House of Commons, with Members voting 203\u201391 against it.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parl.gc.ca/HouseChamberBusiness/ChamberVoteDetail.aspx?Language=E&Mode=1&Parl=41&Ses=1&Vote=466&GroupBy=province&FltrParl=41&FltrSes=1|title=Vote Details (41-1 Vote No. 466)|publisher=[[Parliament of Canada]]|accessdate=2012-09-28|date=2012-09-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://vancouversun.com/news/national/conclude+debate+thorny+abortion+motion/7281699/story.html |publisher=[[Vancouver Sun]] |date=2012-09-21 |title=MPs conclude debate on thorny abortion motion |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120925060906/http://www.vancouversun.com/news/national/conclude%2Bdebate%2Bthorny%2Babortion%2Bmotion/7281699/story.html |archivedate=September 25, 2012 |accessdate=May 13, 2013 }}</ref>\n\n===October to December===\n* October 2 \u2013 A wildfire strikes [[Vita, Manitoba]], destroying at least four houses and one bridge.\n* October 10 \u2013 [[Suicide of Amanda Todd]].\n* October 18 \u2013 The [[Canadian Radio-television and Telecommunications Commission]] rejects [[Bell Media|BCE's]] bid to take over [[Astral Media]], citing that the deal would have given the company too much market power.<ref>{{cite news|title=CRTC rejects BCE takeover of Astral Media|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/story/2012/10/18/pol-parry-crtc-bell.html|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=October 18, 2012|date=October 18, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=CRTC rejects Bell's $3.48 billion buy of Astral Media, worries about competition|url=http://www.thecanadianpress.com/english/online/OnlineFullStory.aspx?filename=DOR-MNN-CP.7e26de37d8a1439c9a4bc6e62890e9fb.CPKEY2008111300&newsitemid=20478823&languageid=1|publisher=The Canadian Press|accessdate=October 18, 2012|date=October 18, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150602221303/http://www.thecanadianpress.com/english/online/OnlineFullStory.aspx?filename=DOR-MNN-CP.7e26de37d8a1439c9a4bc6e62890e9fb.CPKEY2008111300&newsitemid=20478823&languageid=1|archivedate=June 2, 2015|df=}}</ref>\n* October 25\n** Eight children are injured after a van crashes into a school classroom in [[St. Paul, Alberta]].  One of the children would die in hospital the next day.\n** The municipality of [[Wawa, Ontario|Wawa]], [[Ontario]], is forced to declare a [[state of emergency]] after severe flooding washes out several roadways in the municipality, including sections of both [[Ontario Highway 17|Highway 17]] (the main route of the [[Trans-Canada Highway]]) and [[Ontario Highway 101|Highway 101]].<ref>[http://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/northern-ontario-flooding-may-cause-millions-in-damage-1.1013338 \"Northern Ontario flooding may cause millions in damage\"]. [[CTV News]], October 27, 2012.</ref>\n** The Supreme Court upholds the election result in [[Etobicoke Centre (electoral district)|Etobicoke Centre]], with Conservative MP [[Ted Opitz]] keeping his seat.<ref>{{cite news|title=Supreme Court upholds Conservative win in Toronto riding|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/story/2012/10/25/pol-supreme-court-etobicoke-centre-ruling.html|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=October 25, 2012|date=October 25, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Supreme Court makes the right call on election \u2014 but only just|url=http://www2.macleans.ca/2012/10/25/supreme-court-makes-the-right-call-on-election-but-only-just/|publisher=Maclean's|accessdate=October 25, 2012|date=October 25, 2012}}</ref>\n* October 26 \u2013 20th anniversary of the referendum of [[Charlottetown Accord]].\n* October 27 \u2013 A 7.7-magnitude [[2012 Haida Gwaii earthquake|earthquake]] strikes off the coast of [[Moresby Island]]. A small [[tsunami]] occurred not long after the quake.<ref>{{cite news|title='Like a massive wind': B.C. earthquake stories|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/story/2012/10/28/bc-earthquake-witnesses.html|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=November 8, 2012|date=October 28, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=7.7 magnitude quake hits Canada's British Columbia|url=http://ca.news.yahoo.com/magnitude-7-7-earthquake-hits-canadas-british-columbia-032417518.html|publisher=Yahoo News|accessdate=November 8, 2012|date=October 28, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121101022344/http://ca.news.yahoo.com/magnitude-7-7-earthquake-hits-canadas-british-columbia-032417518.html|archivedate=November 1, 2012|df=}}</ref>\n* November 2 \u2013 [[Judith Guichon]] becomes [[Lieutenant Governor of British Columbia]], replacing [[Steven Point]].\n* November 5 - [[G\u00e9rald Tremblay]] resigns as mayor of [[Montreal]], following allegations of corruption within the city government at the provincial [[Charbonneau commission]].\n* November 8 \u2013 An explosion in [[Sherbrooke]] kills two people and injures almost 20 more.<ref>{{cite web|title=Explosion, fire at Quebec plant kills two; 19 more sent to hospital|url=http://www.thecanadianpress.com/english/online/OnlineFullStory.aspx?filename=DOR-MNN-CP.09e335c34cff4a938aebe30a53988f95.CPKEY2008111303&newsitemid=20701984&languageid=1|publisher=The Canadian Press|accessdate=November 8, 2012|date=November 8, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150602221855/http://www.thecanadianpress.com/english/online/OnlineFullStory.aspx?filename=DOR-MNN-CP.09e335c34cff4a938aebe30a53988f95.CPKEY2008111303&newsitemid=20701984&languageid=1|archivedate=June 2, 2015|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=2 killed, 19 injured after Sherbrooke factory explosion|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/story/2012/11/08/sherbrooke-explosion-industrial-park-pepin.html|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=November 8, 2012|date=November 8, 2012}}</ref>\n* November 9 - [[Gilles Vaillancourt]], the mayor of [[Laval, Quebec|Laval]], [[Quebec]] since 1989, resigns following allegations of corruption within Laval's city government at the provincial Charbonneau commission.<ref name=\"CBCNov9\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/story/2012/11/09/quebec-laval-mayor-gilles-vaillancourt-announces-political-future.html|title=Laval mayor resigns amid corruption allegations|date=2012-11-09|publisher=[[CBC News]]|accessdate=9 November 2012|location=Montreal}}</ref>\n* November 16 - [[Michael Applebaum]] is selected as the new [[Mayor of Montreal]] in a council vote, winning 31 votes to 29 for challenger [[Richard Deschamps]].<ref name=ctv>[http://montreal.ctvnews.ca/michael-applebaum-elected-mayor-of-montreal-1.1041058 \"Michael Applebaum elected mayor of Montreal\"]. [[CTV News]], November 16, 2012.</ref>\n* November 23 - [[Alexandre Duplessis]] is selected as the new mayor of [[Laval, Quebec]] in a council vote, winning 15 to three over challenger Jacques St-Jean.<ref name=duplessis>[https://montrealgazette.com/news/Alexandre+Duplessis+elected+interim+mayor+Laval/7600730/story.html \"Alexandre Duplessis elected new interim mayor of Laval\"]. ''[[The Gazette (Montreal)|The Gazette]]'', November 23, 2012.</ref>\n* November 26 \u2013 Three [[2012 Canadian federal by-elections|federal by-elections]]. The [[Conservative Party of Canada|Conservatives]] won [[Calgary Centre]] (Alberta) and [[Durham (electoral district)|Durham]] (Ontario), and the [[New Democratic Party of Canada|New Democratics]] won in [[Victoria (electoral district)|Victoria]] (British Columbia).\n* December 3 - [[Health Canada]] suspended the licence of Chemi Pharmaceutical Inc., after finding falsified test results, during a [[health]] [[inspection#Government|inspection]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hc-sc.gc.ca/ahc-asc/media/advisories-avis/_2012/2012_184lt-eng.php|title=Health Canada Suspends Licence of Chemical Testing Laboratory for Providing Falsified Results|publisher=Health Canada|accessdate=2012-12-04|date=2012-12-04}}</ref>\n\n==Arts and literature==\n\n===Art===\n* May 29 - [[Jim Unger]], creator of the widely syndicated ''[[Herman (comic strip)|Herman]]'', dies at home in Saanich.<ref>{{cite news|last=Stewart|first=John|title=Cartoonist Jim Unger created Herman|url=http://www.mississauga.com/news/article/1364201--cartoonist-jim-unger-created-herman|accessdate=31 May 2012|newspaper=Mississauga News|date=30 May 2012|location=Mississauga ON|quote=Jim Unger, who turned his accidental career as a cartoonist drawing for The Mississauga Times into the worldwide Everyman cartoon character known as Herman, died in his sleep on Tuesday (May 28) at his home in Saanich, B.C.}}</ref>\n\n===Film===\n\n===Music===\n{{main|2012 in Canadian music}}\n\n===Television===\n{{main|2012 in Canadian television}}\nNew channels launched were Sportsnews, [[ABC Spark]], [[Ici Explora|Explora]], and [[Nat Geo Wild]]; leaving the air waves were [[Dusk (TV channel)|Dusk]], and [[Fox Sports World Canada]]. Scheduled to launch are [[Cartoon Network (Canada)|Cartoon Network]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/tbss-cartoon-network-is-headed-286621 |title=TBS's Cartoon Network is Headed to Canada |publisher=Hollywoodreporter.com |date=2011-11-17 |accessdate=2012-08-10 |first=Etan |last=Vlessing}}</ref><ref>[http://www.winnipegfreepress.com/arts-and-life/entertainment/TV/cartoon-networkadult-swim-channel-to-launch-in-canada-on-july-4-150032155.html Cartoon Network/Adult Swim channel to launch in Canada on July 4] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120709054754/http://www.winnipegfreepress.com/arts-and-life/entertainment/TV/cartoon-networkadult-swim-channel-to-launch-in-canada-on-july-4-150032155.html |date=July 9, 2012 }}</ref> and a regional news channel operated by [[Global BC]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Shaw Media to Launch All-News Network in BC|url=http://www.broadcastermagazine.com/news/shaw-media-to-launch-all-news-network-in-bc/1000817210/|accessdate=22 May 2012|newspaper=Broadcaster|date=11 January 2012|quote=Shaw Media announced today that it has filed an application with the Canadian Radio-Television Telecommunications Commission for a regional, Global BC-driven all-news specialty channel. Shaw Media is expected to launch B.C.'s first all-news channel by the summer of 2012.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120122024319/http://www.broadcastermagazine.com/news/shaw-media-to-launch-all-news-network-in-bc/1000817210/|archive-date=22 January 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nNew series include ''[[Total Drama: Revenge of the Island]]'' (January 5), ''[[Mr. D]]'' (January 9), ''[[Arctic Air]]'' (January 10), ''[[The L.A. Complex]]'' (January 10), ''[[Les Bleus de Ramville]]'' (January 19), ''[[Undercover Boss Canada]]'' (February 2), ''[[Canada's Got Talent]]'' (March 4), ''[[Saving Hope]]'' (June 7), ''[[Over the Rainbow]]'' (September 16), ''[[The Bachelor Canada]]'' (October 3).\n\n===Literature===\n*[[Will Ferguson]] wins the [[Scotiabank Giller Prize]] for ''[[419 (novel)|419]]''.\n\n==Sport==\n* January 2\u20135: [[2012 World Junior Ice Hockey Championships]] relegation round and finals \u2013 Calgary, Alberta\n* January 16\u201322: [[2012 Canadian Figure Skating Championships]] \u2013 Moncton, New Brunswick\n* February 1\u20135: [[2012 Molson Canadian Men's Provincial Curling Championship]] \u2013 St. John, New Brunswick\n* February 19\u201326: [[2012 Scotties Tournament of Hearts]] \u2013 Red Deer, Alberta\n* March 3\u201311: [[2012 Tim Hortons Brier]] \u2013 Saskatoon, Saskatchewan\n*May 27 - [