{"title_page": "Keith Faulkner", "text_new": "{{About|the English actor|the British academic|Keith W. Faulkner|the English bass-baritone singer|Keith Falkner}}\n{{BLP sources|date=April 2020}}'''Keith Faulkner''' (born 25 July 1936 in [[Municipal Borough of Richmond (Surrey)|Richmond]], [[Surrey]]) is an English-born Australian film and television actor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2ba5a4f67d|title=Keith Faulkner|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nFaulkner started his career at Corona Academy at the age of eleven and moved on to an adult career in film and television in the late 1950s and early 1960s before leaving the \"business\" and moving to [[Australia]], with the Telephone Rentals[[telecommunications]] company he then worked with, along with his wife Pat and two sons Lee and Simon. In the late 1940s, he appeared at the [[London Coliseum]] in ''Annie Get Your Gun'' playing Annie Oakley's brother Little Jake. In 1951, he appeared at [[Stratford-upon-Avon]]'s [[Royal Shakespeare Theatre|Memorial Theatre]] during the [[Festival of Britain]] Season, playing Falstaff's Page in ''Henry IV'' and the Boy in ''Henry V''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://theatricalia.com/person/2cd/keith-faulkner|title=Keith Faulkner - Theatricalia|website=theatricalia.com}}</ref> This was followed by an extensive tour of Britain with the Elizabethen Theatre Company, performing various Shakespearean productions. In the 1950s, Keith Faulkner was known for his roles as Ginger in ''Just William'' and Bob Cherry in ''[[Billy Bunter]] of [[Greyfriars School]]'' (both BBC TV series) and also featured in juvenile roles in a number of feature films. In the early 1960s, he appeared in several [[B-film]] thrillers and crime films and starred in ''[[The Man in the Back Seat]]'', and ''[[Strongroom (film)|Strongroom]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=V7vPDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA1741&lpg=PA1741&dq=keith+faulkner+The+Encyclopedia+of+British+Film:+Fourth+edition&source=bl&ots=Grc-14zNRh&sig=Uab155Gh9kzveCDgKWbjEeWIy6I&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjG-Im-kcHVAhXCZ1AKHZUEChEQ6AEIMjAC#v=onepage&q=keith+faulkner+The+Encyclopedia+of+British+Film:+Fourth+edition&f=false|title=The Encyclopedia of British Film: Fourth edition|first=Brian|last=McFarlane|date=16 May 2016|publisher=Oxford University Press|via=Google Books}}</ref> His last screen credit was in 1963.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmovie.com/artist/keith-faulkner-p22849|title=Keith Faulkner - Movies and Filmography - AllMovie|website=AllMovie}}</ref>\n\n==Partial filmography==\n* ''[[The Happiest Days of Your Life]]'' (1950)\n* ''[[Laxdale Hall]]'' (1953)\n* ''[[Johnny on the Run]]'' (1953)\n* ''[[The Blue Peter (1955 film)|The Blue Peter]]''  (1955)\n* ''[[Yangtse Incident (film)|Yangtse Incident]]'' (1957)\n* ''[[Tunes of Glory]]'' (1960)\n* ''[[Linda (1960 film)|Linda]]'' (1960)\n* ''[[The Sinister Man]]'' (1961)\n* ''[[Payroll (film)|Payroll]]'' (1961)\n* ''[[The Man in the Back Seat]]'' (1961)\n* ''[[The Pot Carriers]]'' (1962)\n* ''[[Strongroom (film)|Strongroom]]'' (1962)\n* ''[[It's All Happening (film)|It's All Happening]]'' (1963)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|0269091|Keith Faulkner}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Faulkner, Keith}}\n[[Category:1939 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English male film actors]]\n[[Category:English male child actors]]\n[[Category:English emigrants to Australia]]\n\n\n{{England-actor-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{About|the English actor|the British academic|Keith W. Faulkner|the English bass-baritone singer|Keith Falkner}}\n{{BLP sources|date=April 2020}}\n{{BLP IMDb only|date=December 2012}}\n\n'''Keith Faulkner''' (born 25 July 1936 in [[Municipal Borough of Richmond (Surrey)|Richmond]], [[Surrey]]) is an English-born Australian film and television actor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2ba5a4f67d|title=Keith Faulkner|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nFaulkner started his career at Corona Academy at the age of eleven and moved on to an adult career in film and television in the late 1950s and early 1960s before leaving the \"business\" and moving to [[Australia]], with the Telephone Rentals[[telecommunications]] company he then worked with, along with his wife Pat and two sons Lee and Simon. In the late 1940s, he appeared at the [[London Coliseum]] in ''Annie Get Your Gun'' playing Annie Oakley's brother Little Jake. In 1951, he appeared at [[Stratford-upon-Avon]]'s [[Royal Shakespeare Theatre|Memorial Theatre]] during the [[Festival of Britain]] Season, playing Falstaff's Page in ''Henry IV'' and the Boy in ''Henry V''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://theatricalia.com/person/2cd/keith-faulkner|title=Keith Faulkner - Theatricalia|website=theatricalia.com}}</ref> This was followed by an extensive tour of Britain with the Elizabethen Theatre Company, performing various Shakespearean productions. In the 1950s, Keith Faulkner was known for his roles as Ginger in ''Just William'' and Bob Cherry in ''[[Billy Bunter]] of [[Greyfriars School]]'' (both BBC TV series) and also featured in juvenile roles in a number of feature films. In the early 1960s, he appeared in several [[B-film]] thrillers and crime films and starred in ''[[The Man in the Back Seat]]'', and ''[[Strongroom (film)|Strongroom]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=V7vPDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA1741&lpg=PA1741&dq=keith+faulkner+The+Encyclopedia+of+British+Film:+Fourth+edition&source=bl&ots=Grc-14zNRh&sig=Uab155Gh9kzveCDgKWbjEeWIy6I&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjG-Im-kcHVAhXCZ1AKHZUEChEQ6AEIMjAC#v=onepage&q=keith+faulkner+The+Encyclopedia+of+British+Film:+Fourth+edition&f=false|title=The Encyclopedia of British Film: Fourth edition|first=Brian|last=McFarlane|date=16 May 2016|publisher=Oxford University Press|via=Google Books}}</ref> His last screen credit was in 1963.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmovie.com/artist/keith-faulkner-p22849|title=Keith Faulkner - Movies and Filmography - AllMovie|website=AllMovie}}</ref>\n\n==Partial filmography==\n* ''[[The Happiest Days of Your Life]]'' (1950)\n* ''[[Laxdale Hall]]'' (1953)\n* ''[[Johnny on the Run]]'' (1953)\n* ''[[The Blue Peter (1955 film)|The Blue Peter]]''  (1955)\n* ''[[Yangtse Incident (film)|Yangtse Incident]]'' (1957)\n* ''[[Tunes of Glory]]'' (1960)\n* ''[[Linda (1960 film)|Linda]]'' (1960)\n* ''[[The Sinister Man]]'' (1961)\n* ''[[Payroll (film)|Payroll]]'' (1961)\n* ''[[The Man in the Back Seat]]'' (1961)\n* ''[[The Pot Carriers]]'' (1962)\n* ''[[Strongroom (film)|Strongroom]]'' (1962)\n* ''[[It's All Happening (film)|It's All Happening]]'' (1963)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|0269091|Keith Faulkner}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Faulkner, Keith}}\n[[Category:1939 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English male film actors]]\n[[Category:English male child actors]]\n[[Category:English emigrants to Australia]]\n\n\n{{England-actor-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Cardiffbear88", "label": "safe", "comment": "Amend tags", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Keith_Faulkner"}
{"title_page": "Dump Trump (statue)", "text_new": "[[File:Trumprobottrafalgar.jpg|thumb|\"Dumping Trump\" Robot at 2019 Trafalgar Square demonstration]]\n{{short description|Statue of U.S. President Donald Trump}}\n{{Distinguish|Statue of Donald Trump}}\n{{Infobox artwork\n| title = Dump Trump\n| other_language_1 = \n| other_title_1 = \n| other_language_2 = \n| other_title_2 = \n| wikidata = \n| image =\n| image_upright = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| artist = [[Don Lessem]]\n| year = {{start date|2019}}\n| completion_date = <!-- For a more specific date (post-1583): {{start date|YYYY|MM|DD|df=y}} -->\n| catalogue = \n| medium = \n| movement = \n| subject = [[Donald Trump]]\n| height_metric = <!-- (i.e. in metric units) -->\n| width_metric = \n| length_metric = \n| diameter_metric = \n| height_imperial = 16\n| width_imperial = \n| length_imperial = \n| diameter_imperial = \n| dimensions = \n| dimensions_ref = \n| metric_unit = m  <!-- Note: this parameter must either use the value given or not be included -->\n| imperial_unit = ft  <!-- Note: this parameter must either use the value given or not be included -->\n| weight = \n| designation = \n| condition = \n| museum = \n| city = \n| coordinates = <!-- Only use for the coordinates (when known) of the artwork itself, i.e. not for the site, building, structure, etc where it is kept, otherwise leave blank (or omit): {{coord|LAT|LON|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} -->\n| owner = \n| accession = \n| preceded_by = <!-- preceding work by the same artist -->\n| followed_by = <!-- next work by the same artist -->\n| module = \n| website = <!-- Official webpage/site only: {{URL|example.com}} -->\n}}\n'''''Dump Trump''''' is a {{convert|16|ft}} high statue of [[United States]] president [[Donald Trump]] sitting on a golden toilet. The sculpture was temporarily installed in Central London's [[Trafalgar Square]] ahead of his 2019 visit to the [[United Kingdom]], and displayed during the Trump-organized [[Salute to America]] in Washington, D.C., on July 4, 2019.\n\n==Description and history==\n[[File:Dump Trump Tuesday Trafalgar Square 1866.jpg|thumb|Dump Trump Rally in London's Trafalgar Square]]\nIn addition to depicting Donald Trump [[tweeting]] from a [[smartphone]] on a golden toilet while wearing a [[MAGA hat]] with \"[[Efforts to impeach Donald Trump|IMPEACH ME!]]\" scribbled on it, the {{Convert|16|ft|m|adj=on}} statue makes [[flatulence]] noises and says the phrases \"I'm a very stable genius\", \"no collusion\", \"witch-hunt\", and \"you are fake news\", popular and common phrases said by Trump during his presidency. The statue was designed by [[Don Lessem]] and cost approximately $25,000.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/trump-protests-toilet-robot-tweeting-trafalgar-square-london-state-visit-a8943061.html|title=Giant model of Trump sitting on golden toilet tweeting appears in central London|date=2019-06-04|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=2019-06-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/06/04/the-giant-trump-baby-and-other-stunts-that-took-on-the-president.html|title=The giant Trump baby and other stunts that took on the president \u2014 and polarized opinion|last=Handley|first=Lucy|date=2019-06-04|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=2019-06-04}}</ref>\n\nLessem, from Philadelphia, built the statue and had it shipped by boat across the Atlantic. A [[dinosaur]] expert who makes models of prehistoric creatures for museums, he said, \"I'm interested in things that are big, not very intelligent and have lost their place in history.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Trump baby blimp 'stabbed with sharp object' by pro-Trump supporter |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/trump-baby-blimp-stabbed-london-protest-parliament-square-a8943976.html |accessdate=5 June 2019 |work=The Independent |date=4 June 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe statue was temporarily installed in Central London's [[Trafalgar Square]] ahead of his 2019 visit to the [[United Kingdom]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/uk-news/dump-trump-protest-model-president-16376671|title=Dump Trump protest attracts activists to Trafalgar Square|last=Worden|first=Andy|last2=Gibbons|first2=Brett|date=2019-06-04|website=walesonline|access-date=2019-06-04}}</ref> It was displayed during the Trump-organized [[Salute to America]] event in [[Washington, D.C.]] on July 4, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehill.com/blogs/blog-briefing-room/news/451607-giant-trump-robot-tweeting-on-toilet-being-brought-to-dc-to|title=Giant robot Trump tweeting on toilet coming to DC to protest Fourth >celebration|last=Folley|first=Aris|date=2019-07-03|website=TheHill|language=en|access-date=2019-07-05}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[2019 in art]]\n* ''[[The Emperor Has No Balls]]''\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Protests against Trump footer}}\n{{Portal bar|London|Politics|Visual arts}}\n\n[[Category:2019 in London]]\n[[Category:2019 in politics]]\n[[Category:2019 protests]]\n[[Category:2019 works]]\n[[Category:Outdoor sculptures in London]]\n[[Category:Parodies of Donald Trump]]\n[[Category:Political art]]\n[[Category:Protests against Donald Trump]]\n[[Category:Protests in London]]\n[[Category:Statues in London]]\n[[Category:Statues of Donald Trump]]\n[[Category:Trafalgar Square]]\n\n{{sculpture-stub}}\n{{US-poli-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Statue of U.S. President Donald Trump}}\n{{Distinguish|Statue of Donald Trump}}\n{{Infobox artwork\n| title = Dump Trump\n| other_language_1 = \n| other_title_1 = \n| other_language_2 = \n| other_title_2 = \n| wikidata = \n| image =\n| image_upright = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| artist = [[Don Lessem]]\n| year = {{start date|2019}}\n| completion_date = <!-- For a more specific date (post-1583): {{start date|YYYY|MM|DD|df=y}} -->\n| catalogue = \n| medium = \n| movement = \n| subject = [[Donald Trump]]\n| height_metric = <!-- (i.e. in metric units) -->\n| width_metric = \n| length_metric = \n| diameter_metric = \n| height_imperial = 16\n| width_imperial = \n| length_imperial = \n| diameter_imperial = \n| dimensions = \n| dimensions_ref = \n| metric_unit = m  <!-- Note: this parameter must either use the value given or not be included -->\n| imperial_unit = ft  <!-- Note: this parameter must either use the value given or not be included -->\n| weight = \n| designation = \n| condition = \n| museum = \n| city = \n| coordinates = <!-- Only use for the coordinates (when known) of the artwork itself, i.e. not for the site, building, structure, etc where it is kept, otherwise leave blank (or omit): {{coord|LAT|LON|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} -->\n| owner = \n| accession = \n| preceded_by = <!-- preceding work by the same artist -->\n| followed_by = <!-- next work by the same artist -->\n| module = \n| website = <!-- Official webpage/site only: {{URL|example.com}} -->\n}}\n'''''Dump Trump''''' is a {{convert|16|ft}} high statue of [[United States]] president [[Donald Trump]] sitting on a golden toilet. The sculpture was temporarily installed in Central London's [[Trafalgar Square]] ahead of his 2019 visit to the [[United Kingdom]], and displayed during the Trump-organized [[Salute to America]] in Washington, D.C., on July 4, 2019.\n\n==Description and history==\n[[File:Dump Trump Tuesday Trafalgar Square 1866.jpg|thumb|Dump Trump Rally in London's Trafalgar Square]]\nIn addition to depicting Donald Trump [[tweeting]] from a [[smartphone]] on a golden toilet while wearing a [[MAGA hat]] with \"[[Efforts to impeach Donald Trump|IMPEACH ME!]]\" scribbled on it, the {{Convert|16|ft|m|adj=on}} statue makes [[flatulence]] noises and says the phrases \"I'm a very stable genius\", \"no collusion\", \"witch-hunt\", and \"you are fake news\", popular and common phrases said by Trump during his presidency. The statue was designed by [[Don Lessem]] and cost approximately $25,000.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/trump-protests-toilet-robot-tweeting-trafalgar-square-london-state-visit-a8943061.html|title=Giant model of Trump sitting on golden toilet tweeting appears in central London|date=2019-06-04|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=2019-06-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/06/04/the-giant-trump-baby-and-other-stunts-that-took-on-the-president.html|title=The giant Trump baby and other stunts that took on the president \u2014 and polarized opinion|last=Handley|first=Lucy|date=2019-06-04|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=2019-06-04}}</ref>\n\nLessem, from Philadelphia, built the statue and had it shipped by boat across the Atlantic. A [[dinosaur]] expert who makes models of prehistoric creatures for museums, he said, \"I'm interested in things that are big, not very intelligent and have lost their place in history.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Trump baby blimp 'stabbed with sharp object' by pro-Trump supporter |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/trump-baby-blimp-stabbed-london-protest-parliament-square-a8943976.html |accessdate=5 June 2019 |work=The Independent |date=4 June 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe statue was temporarily installed in Central London's [[Trafalgar Square]] ahead of his 2019 visit to the [[United Kingdom]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/uk-news/dump-trump-protest-model-president-16376671|title=Dump Trump protest attracts activists to Trafalgar Square|last=Worden|first=Andy|last2=Gibbons|first2=Brett|date=2019-06-04|website=walesonline|access-date=2019-06-04}}</ref> It was displayed during the Trump-organized [[Salute to America]] event in [[Washington, D.C.]] on July 4, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehill.com/blogs/blog-briefing-room/news/451607-giant-trump-robot-tweeting-on-toilet-being-brought-to-dc-to|title=Giant robot Trump tweeting on toilet coming to DC to protest Fourth >celebration|last=Folley|first=Aris|date=2019-07-03|website=TheHill|language=en|access-date=2019-07-05}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[2019 in art]]\n* ''[[The Emperor Has No Balls]]''\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Protests against Trump footer}}\n{{Portal bar|London|Politics|Visual arts}}\n\n[[Category:2019 in London]]\n[[Category:2019 in politics]]\n[[Category:2019 protests]]\n[[Category:2019 works]]\n[[Category:Outdoor sculptures in London]]\n[[Category:Parodies of Donald Trump]]\n[[Category:Political art]]\n[[Category:Protests against Donald Trump]]\n[[Category:Protests in London]]\n[[Category:Statues in London]]\n[[Category:Statues of Donald Trump]]\n[[Category:Trafalgar Square]]\n\n{{sculpture-stub}}\n{{US-poli-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Troodon1", "label": "safe", "comment": "add photo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dump_Trump_(statue)"}
